{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493447"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:11:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:11:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.04,0.06,0.35,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103189"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85626"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2157"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30975"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45065"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103189"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 40-year-old woman presents with a one month history of a painless lump in her left breast. This first came to her attention after she tripped and fell onto her breast, whilst carrying groceries from her car. She did not notice any bruising at the time. She denies any changes to the size of the lump over the last month, nor in the lead-up to her most recent period (which was three weeks ago). In her opinion, the lump has remained fixed in the same position since she first felt it. There has not been any nipple discharge. She reports no significant medical history and does not take any medications. Menarche occurred at age 12. She has two children, aged 16 and 18, who were both breastfed. A photograph of her left breast is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Traumatic fat necrosis","Intraductal papilloma","Fibrocystic breast changes","Invasive ductal carcinoma","Fibroadenoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe photograph of the breast is concerning, as it shows skin tethering and puckering in the infero-lateral quadrant: both are ominous signs suggestive of an \u003Cstrong\u003Einvasive carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient does not have any obvious risk factors for carcinoma of the breast, however in any adult female who presents with a painless breast lump, breast cancer must be on the list of possible causes. In this case, the recent injury to the breast likely drew her attention to the area, prompting self-examination and subsequent discovery of the lump. She requires further work-up, including a detailed examination of both breasts, imaging investigations (ultrasound scan and/or mammography), as well as an ultrasound-guided core biopsy. A referral to a breast surgeon is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic fat necrosis \u003C/strong\u003Ecan cause a breast lump, but it is usually associated with pain. In this case, the fall is a red herring and many women who present with fat necrosis will have no recollection of breast trauma. The asymmetrical structural changes to the left breast shown in the photograph are unlikely to be explained by fat necrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E will often be felt as a hard lump behind the nipple or adjacent to it. A bloody nipple discharge is frequently present. The features of this patient\u0027s presentation, as well as the appearance of the breast in the photograph make intraductal papilloma less likely than breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic breast changes \u003C/strong\u003Ewill typically manifest for the first time in younger females aged in their 20s and 30s. Patients will classically report generalised \u0022lumpiness\u0022 across both breasts, with variation in size of these lumps across the duration of the menstrual cycle. Patients may also report some associated discomfort. This patient does not present with a history suggestive of fibrocystic breast changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E fibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is often referred to a \u0022breast mouse\u0022 due to its mobility. The lump arising from a fibroadenoma will often be felt in different locations of the breast from one day to the next. This patient presents with a fixed lump that has not changed position over the last month. This is more suggestive of a sinister cause rather than a fibroadenoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An asymptomatic distortion of a breast in an older patient is very suggestive of a malignant process."],"references":["Vasei N, Shishegar A, Ghalkhani F, Darvishi M. Fat necrosis in the Breast: A systematic review of clinical. Lipids in Health and Disease. 2019 Jun;18(1):139\u2013139."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85626"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15331"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15331"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3d78216e-1f1b-426d-8246-af0c67b24057.jpg","thumbUrl":"h